# Large example (~5000 chars) to test chunk splitting/overlap with current defaults:
# KbChunking:ChunkSizeChars=2000, ChunkOverlapChars=200
POST {{baseUrl}}/debug/chunk-preview
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "markdown": "# Ops Runbook: HTTP 5xx Spike Triage\n\n## Overview\n\nThis document is intentionally long (about 5000 characters) so you can preview how the chunker splits content by headings and blank lines, and then further splits oversized parts by punctuation and newlines. The goal is to simulate a real ops runbook: it has sections, steps, examples, and notes.\n\n## Step 1 — Confirm the symptom\n\nCheck whether the spike is global or limited to a single endpoint. Start with the most basic questions: when did it start, how fast did it rise, and which services are involved. Look at request rate, error rate, and latency together. If error rate rises while traffic stays flat, suspect a new failure mode. If traffic surges and errors follow, consider overload, queueing, or dependency pressure. Confirm whether the 5xx comes from your service or from a proxy or gateway layer. Also confirm if there are changes in the last 30 minutes: deployments, configuration changes, feature flags, certificate rotations, or infrastructure events. If you have tracing, sample failing traces and compare them with healthy traces. If you do not have tracing, collect request ids from logs, then find correlated errors. Keep the time window narrow: for example, from 10:05 to 10:20, then expand only if needed.\n\n## Step 2 — Classify by status code and error signature\n\nGroup failures by status code family and error signature. For example: 500 with NullReferenceException, 502 from gateway upstream timeout, 503 due to overload, 504 from dependency latency, or 507/509 from resource limits. In logs, look for a stable signature: exception type, message prefix, stack trace top frame, or a dependency host + path. If the failure is not stable, check if the errors are spread across many code paths or concentrated in one route. A concentrated route often means a single handler or a single dependency. A spread pattern often means platform or shared dependency issues.\n\n## Step 3 — Check top dependencies\n\nPick the top 3 dependencies and validate them. If you have metrics, check their error rate and latency. If you only have logs, search for timeouts, connection pool exhaustion, DNS failures, TLS handshake issues, and rate limiting. A common pattern is that a downstream dependency is slow, causing thread pool starvation and timeouts upstream. Another pattern is connection leaks: the pool gets exhausted, then requests back up, then everything fails. Also check whether retries are amplifying traffic; too many retries can turn a small incident into a large one.\n\n## Step 4 — Resource and saturation signals\n\nLook at CPU, memory, GC pause time, thread pool, and queue length. If CPU is high, check whether it correlates with request rate. If memory climbs until OOM, suspect leaks or unbounded caches. If latency rises before errors, suspect saturation; if errors rise without latency, suspect immediate failures like bad config, missing secrets, or auth errors. In Kubernetes, check Pod restarts, readiness failures, and node pressure events. In VM setups, check disk I/O, file descriptor limits, and network errors.\n\n## Step 5 — Recent change review\n\nReview the last deploy. Ask: did the deploy introduce a new dependency call, a new query, or a new payload size? Did it change timeouts or retry policy? Did it change serialization formats? If you can, do a quick rollback to confirm. A rollback is a diagnostic tool: if rollback removes the symptom, you have strong evidence. If rollback does not help, focus on dependencies or infrastructure.\n\n## Example log queries\n\n- Find 5xx in the last 15 minutes and group by endpoint\n- Find timeouts and connection errors\n- Find spikes of 429/503 from downstream\n- Find error signatures by exception type\n\n## Notes\n\nAlways write down what you checked and what you learned. During an incident, the biggest risk is repeated work and unclear ownership. Keep a simple timeline: start time, key observations, top hypotheses, actions taken, and outcomes. This makes the handoff smoother and the postmortem easier.\n\n## Appendix — Clarifying questions\n\nWhen someone reports “5xx is spiking,” ask a few quick questions to reduce guesswork: Which service and which endpoint? What is the exact time window? Is the impact global or only one region? What changed recently: deploy, config, feature flag, traffic pattern, or dependency? Do we see a specific error signature in logs, such as a repeated exception type or a repeated dependency call failing? Can we get one request id or trace id from a failing user report? If the report is vague, it is better to ask these questions first than to send a long generic checklist. The faster you get a concrete endpoint and a narrow time window, the faster you can find the first strong signal in metrics and logs. If you are on-call, keep these questions in a short template and paste them into the incident channel; it saves time and keeps everyone aligned.\n"
}
